<subSubSection id="C33C09E7FFE2FFBB64886A93FE71BDE7" pageId="9" pageNumber="112" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B995A6CFFE2FFBB64886A93FE71BDE7" blockId="9.[151,756,943,1158]" pageId="9" pageNumber="112">
<emphasis id="B952867EFFE2FFBB64886A93FEBBBAA7" bold="true" box="[151,265,943,966]" pageId="9" pageNumber="112">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species-rich genus is nearly worldwidely distributed. At present, 18 species are known from the 
<collectingCountry id="F3311AFCFFE2FFBB65716AD3FE65BD67" box="[366,471,1007,1030]" name="Indonesia" pageId="9" pageNumber="112">Moluccas</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB7279DFFE2FFBB65EE6AD3FD37BD67" author="Lobl I." box="[497,645,1007,1030]" pageId="9" pageNumber="112" pagination="165 - 187" refId="ref11281" refString="Lobl I. 2015 a. Contribution to the knowledge of the Scaphidiinae (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae) of the Moluccas. Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde A, Neue Serie 8: 165 - 187." type="journal article" year="2015">Löbl, 2015a</bibRefCitation>
), all but 
<taxonomicName id="4C2621EFFFE2FFBB64886D33FE6BBD47" authority="Pic, 1915" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1915" box="[151,473,1038,1062]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scaphisoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteomaculatum">
<emphasis id="B952867EFFE2FFBB64886D33FED6BD47" box="[151,356,1038,1062]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="112">S. luteomaculatum</emphasis>
Pic, 1915
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2621EFFFE2FFBB66096D33FF7EBD27" authority="Lobl, 2003" authorityName="Lobl" authorityYear="2003" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scaphisoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coarctatum">
<emphasis id="B952867EFFE2FFBB66096D33FD1DBD47" box="[534,687,1039,1062]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="112">S. coarctatum</emphasis>
Löbl, 2003
</taxonomicName>
possibly endemic. The studied material comprises two additional species, one known previously from Queensland, and a new one.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
